{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17414785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17414785"},"attributes":{"position":42,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T08:58:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T08:58:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12355"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514699"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:25:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:25:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12355"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"12355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12355"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.7,0.05,0.16,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4874"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32160"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4874"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12355"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17833"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7866"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7972"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34074"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42745"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44878"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/32160"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old male presented after a car accident. He complained of penetrating pain and feeling of tingling pins and needles in his lower limbs. He has no significant medical history. On examination his touch and temperature sensation were intact, Romberg\u0027s sign was positive, he was not able to feel the vibration of tuning fork on his legs. His blood pressure was 139/90 mmHg, pulse 95/min and temperature 37.3\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely site of lesion causing the symptoms in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hemi section of cord","Posterior cord lesion","Central cord lesion","Anterior cord lesion","Complete cord transection"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is this case is presenting with sensory ataxia, paraesthesia and loss of position and vibration sense while the pain, touch and temperature are preserved after trauma indicating it to be \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior cord syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. The dorsal column\u2013medial lemniscus pathway in the spinal cord conveys sensations of fine touch, vibration, two-point discrimination, and proprioception (position) from the skin and joints. The pain touch and temperature are preserved as they are conveyed by anterior and lateral spinothalamic tract.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHemi section of spinal cord\u003C/strong\u003E causes paralysis and loss of proprioception on the ipsilateral side as the lesion, and loss of pain and temperature sensation on the contralateral side as the lesion. Touch is spared as it passes through dorsal and lateral columns of both sides. This doesn\u0027t match patient\u0027s condition. Brown-Sequard syndrome may be caused by injury to the spinal cord resulting from a spinal cord tumor, trauma, ischemia, or infectious or inflammatory diseases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral cord lesion\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by loss of movement in arms and hands usually from trauma leading to major injury to the central corticospinal tract of the spinal cord. Loss of pain and temperature on one or both sides occur over a number of dermatomes with normal sensation above and below and is called suspended sensory loss. Bladder dysfunction and urinary retention may also be present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior cord lesion\u003C/strong\u003E is commonly caused by ischemia of the anterior spinal artery, resulting in loss of function of the anterior two-thirds of the spinal cord. Complete motor paralysis and loss of pain and temperature below the level of the lesion due to interruption of the corticospinal tract and spinothalamic tract respectively. Proprioception and vibratory sensation are preserved due to intact dorsal column.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete cord transection \u003C/strong\u003Eusually occurs due to penetrating injuries such as knife wounds or severe trauma such as vertebral fracture\u2013dislocations or a complicated childbirth. It presents with loss of all sensations below the level of lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome of the important spinal tracts have been shown in the following image:\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Posterior cord lesion presents with loss of position and vibration sense while the pain, touch and temperature are preserved."],"references":["McKinley W, Hills A, Sima A. Posterior cord syndrome: Demographics and rehabilitation outcomes. J Spinal Cord Med. 2021 Mar;44(2):241-246."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17833"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12355"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19045"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19045"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6e15366c-0784-43c4-b6f4-967f0e0c0ef3.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6e15366c-0784-43c4-b6f4-967f0e0c0ef3.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":781,"height":596}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17833"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-02-04T04:48:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T16:18:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4874"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32160"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":